### Inheritance in Java

Inheritance allows a class to inherit fields and methods from another class. It establishes an "is-a" relationship.

---

### Inheritance Syntax

```java
class ChildClass extends ParentClass {
    // inherits all public and protected members
}
```

---

### Types of Inheritance

| Type | Description |
|------|-------------|
| Single | One child extends one parent |
| Multilevel | A extends B extends C |
| Hierarchical | Multiple children extend one parent |

Java does NOT support multiple inheritance of classes (to avoid the diamond problem).

---

### The `extends` Keyword

```java
class Animal {
    void eat() {
        System.out.println("Animal eats");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    void bark() {
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }
}
// Dog inherits eat() from Animal
```

---

### What is Inherited?

| Inherited | Not Inherited |
|-----------|---------------|
| public fields/methods | private fields/methods |
| protected fields/methods | Constructors |
| default (same package) | Static methods (hidden, not inherited) |

> **Key Point:** Java uses `extends` for class inheritance. A class can extend only one parent class. The `Object` class is the root of all Java classes — every class implicitly extends `Object`.

codeExample:
class Animal {
    String name;

    Animal(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    void eat() {
        System.out.println(name + " is eating");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    Dog(String name) {
        super(name);
    }

    void bark() {
        System.out.println(name + " is barking");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Dog dog = new Dog("Buddy");
        dog.eat();   // inherited from Animal
        dog.bark();  // defined in Dog
    }
}
